segments.text: Now where did you go after officer school?
From, this unit was also there, well it was at Camp Wood.
What, Leonard Wood?
No.
No?
No, it was, I'm not sure what the other name was.
It was just four or five miles outside of Fort Monmouth.
Okay, I see.
It was at the same place we went through our,

was, I recall, what they called it, POM or something training, overseas training, where you crawl under the machine gun fire, you go through the gas drills and throw grenades and this sort of thing, fired on the rifle range and various things as this.
Preparation for overseas movement is, I believe, what they called it.
And from there, why?
went to, as a unit on the train, a troop train to California and went overseas on the USS Merline, which was at one time a pleasure craft of the Matson line running from Frisco to Hawaii.
And it was... What was this unit's designation?
We went to New Guinea.
No, no destination.
What was it called?
Do you remember?
Did it have a number, et cetera?
0964H, Casual Detachment, 0964H.

And it was actually the entire detachment were made up of two headquarters teams, which was a company commander, a supply officer, a company clerk, and a first sergeant, and I don't remember whether they had a mess sergeant or not, but it was a team supposedly could go in and operate a company.
There were two of these teams.
There were ten of the radio teams that were called three position radio teams where you operate from one place, your receivers are remote site and transmitters are another remote site.
These units each had two officers and about 20 men.
The switchboard team were called a three position switchboard team which meant you had a
place for three switchboard operators sitting side by side.
We had a cable splicer, an installer repairman.
In other words, this unit could not only set up and operate the switchboard, but all the connecting phones and trunks to other switchboards, this sort of capability.
When did you sail?
Do you remember what month and year you sailed?
It was in October, about the 10th of October.
And 44.
44, excuse me.
They made the invasion of Lady, I think, while we were on the boat.
And so you went to New Guinea.
And we started at New Guinea.
We were supposed to have gone into Australia and were running out of fresh water.
And Brisbane was not deep enough harbor for them to take on fresh water.
So we went to Milne Bay and from there on to Oro Bay, which is where we

debarked and then oh a number of us had problems with the company commander and got transferred out as fast as we could and I went to a heavy construction company which was a full line type construction company up at Alanya.
What was the designation of this unit?
This unit was company C of the 52nd Signal Battalion.
This was a
a signal battalion that had been in, started out in Australia.
It was broken down into, I believe there were two heavy construction companies and an operating company, radio, message center type set up, and a headquarters company.
For roughly two weeks while I was there, the month that I was there at Helania, it was the only time I ever saw anything of our
other than just the company we were sent as a separate company and later even split to separate platoons, company and different task force.
You said you were there about a month?
At Hylania about a month and then we went to Lady.
From Lady uh oh we had just got an assignment to

rebuild a line over what they call the Ormont corridor and these were changed and we were sent to Mindoro where we joined with the 41st division which had been come up all the way from Australia, New Guinea, Boonah, Finch Haven, a number of these places

at the end of the war this Major Helles who was a signal officer over us as a separate unit I think the first first list of coming home with number of points he was on it he'd been there this long and it was a unit that had been through a lot but
But at Mendora, this is where we split the company, and we went and split the cooks, split the company clerks.
Of course, we had construction platoons that were already separated, and we went as a separate platoon then to Palawan in the Philippines with the 186th Regiment as a regimental combat team.

I don't recall, spent probably three or four months there and later rejoined the company and the rest of the division down at Zamboanga where they had gone in as an invasion and the same type thing where ours was there at Palawan.
I think they had probably more opposition down there.
Were you all following the combat troops in to do your particular work?
Yes, we were assigned in splitting the division.
Signal Company, they didn't have enough personnel to accomplish their mission of telephone and what have you.
And we went in, started off stringing field wire and what have you.
And as soon as ours was over pretty quick, in close at least,
This was at Port Princesa where we went in, but then we started some pole line construction for the various units.
There were a number of aviation engineering battalions there building, rebuilding the runway.
This seemed to have been a place where any time a plane was flying,
back and forth, and I'm not sure from where to where, Lady or what have you, to the island south where they had come from and they had any bombs left.
They dropped them here.
So the engineers had a pretty rough time getting this rebuilt.
Did you all come under any fire while you were doing here?
Oh, not really.
In other words, the area was fairly well cleared before y'all went in and laid lines?
Well, there are some of our working and right-of-ways that may be standing there with a pair of pliers and see Jaffa and both of them was ready to bail out, but primarily it was a cleared area.
We used to have a lone
air raid, long plane making an air raid once in a while, this sort of thing, but not, not a concentrated effort.
There, there were lots of, and I say lots, there were a number of individual Japanese soldiers and there were, they had a small penal

group or prison for them where they would bring them in but this was an island that well I guess it's claim to fame was it had two penal colonies there that were still operating as penal colonies under the chaps and under after they were freed lots of them were
lifers, this type of thing.
From where?
I think primarily they were shipped down from Manila.
Were they mainly Filipinos?
They were all Filipinos, yes.
These were Filipino prison institutes.
And what island is this on now?
This is on Palawan.
Palawan, okay.
But I had dinner with the
the warden on one occasion.

We of course they had a telephone system of the sort and we had some equipment people that helped rehab it for him and this Major Helles that I'd mentioned before and I went over and had dinner with him.
He was told us some of the things.
This is the one time

censorship almost got our unit in trouble because some of the men had been over it or that were working over there happened to take a picture where these this was prisoners that of the penal colony had been jumped working out in the fields and they'd been jumped by some japs and they were apparently so hungry that once they

took over their food they got so busy eating they weren't paying attention and these Filipinos had proceeded to chop their head off with a machete and this picture was of these three guys standing there with a head in the bucket and of course that I'm not real sure where the

whether, as I recall, one of the guys went to the censor wanting to know if he could send it home and this closed down an illicit sort of developing photo lab that one of them had blown to one of these units that had been operating.
Oh my.
And then could you go on?
Well from

after rejoining the company at Zamboango we were of course then went back almost to a basic training type situation with the 41st Division preparing and we had already been assigned a place to land in Japan with the 41st when the end of the war came and at this time then
We disbanded the Company C of the 52nd Signal Battalion and I went back to Lady and was wire officer there at Lady for a period of probably six or seven more months before I came home.
What did you do after you arrived home?
Of course, I got home, as I recall, in the end of May, first of June.
And I don't remember specifically about how I went about it, but I knew I was going back to A&M to finish.
And I had the summer.
I spent some time.
My parents, in the meantime, had gone to Oak Ridge, Tennessee.
And they were there when I got out of the service, where I'd
going in on active duty there in Louisiana.
I was discharged at Camp McCoy, Wisconsin, and from there down to Tennessee.
I had a sister and brother-in-law that lived in Rochester, New York, and I went up there for a week or two before coming back down to A&M to finish up.
So when did you start back to A&M?
I started back in
September, October, whenever, September of 46.
And graduated in June of 47, May of 47.
So you only had about a year to go.
Yes, I liked a year.
Were there many veterans there when you got there?
Yes, there were lots of them.
Where did you live when you got there?
I don't remember now, 14 I believe it was.
Yes, 13 or 14.
This was the next newer dorms over on the north side of the campus.
In the Sebesa area.
In the Sebesa area, right.
These were built very similar to 1 to 12 over in the Duncan area, but they were added down in behind
You went to school then on the GI Bill?
Yes, on the GI Bill.
How much were they paying you?
Do you remember how that worked?
Not really.
I was reading an article in the paper where they were trying to compare it in those days with now.
They did pay all the tuition, all your books, and what have you, and we had

I just don't remember if I had to guess I would have said 75 as I recall the paper said something about 115 dollars a month cash but really this I was single I've been single and there hadn't been many places spend any money overseas so this part of it wasn't wasn't this hard at this time
Do you remember seeing any changes in the campus when you got back?
Any attitudes, or were you seeing much change in the way things were going on?
Did it seem changed?
I don't recall that there was this much change other than going to class, this kind of thing.
Most of these were the same profs you had in EE.
It's a smaller group.

possibly than some of the other departments, but they were all leaning over backwards to help you, to give you the benefit of the doubt, or what have you, knowing that you'd been gone for two, two and a half years, something like this.
Was there much friction between the new civilian students and the Corps of Cadets then?
I don't really recall any particular at all.
We of course ate in Sabisa running downstairs as a cafeteria type thing with the great influx.

like seven o'clock classes so you were getting down there to eat breakfast pretty early if you went to breakfast and on to class and what have you so and of course by now there are many more cars on the campus and you weren't particularly tied down to the campus so that
So you really didn't notice too many changes.
You came back and sort of fitted right in without having any adjustment problems.
I didn't feel that many of us didn't.
Probably those who had the biggest adjustment problem were those who had married and started families during their time in the service.
They were living in the
barracks that had been moved in off over on the north side of the campus there.
And these were little bitty apartments and... Did you have any friends who were in the Corps then at that time?
I don't recall any in the Corps particularly.
These were all...
So most of your friends that you had were all veterans?
Right, right.
This was the group you associated with.
a big part.

Actually just laying out this one summer I was in a sense one a half a semester but also required courses and some of this it took me a year many of those who had were in the class of 44 still like a semester certainly to finish and were there so most of you I mean they were
plenty of those you'd been associated with all of us living in nearly all of us living in the same dorm there.
Were things a lot more crowded then?
We were living always then at least three in a room.
Now when you graduated do you recall let's see how old the phrase is
What was your first job after you graduated?
Well, since I had some more GI Bill available, my older sister was trying to talk me into coming to New York and live with her and take some business.
My dad was urging me to get a master's or something, but I ended up not really having made up my mind.
came back to Corpus and went to work as a German electrician at an electric construction company and I've been there ever since.
Oh after about six months working with the tools I started estimating and nights and eventually into the office full-time and now
What was your connection?
How did you go back on your work for electric construction?
I went down.
I had worked out of the local union, and it was just by chance that I went there.
They had a request in for me, and this is where I was sent.
So you've been there ever since.
And what's your current position with them now?
I'm president.
When did you become president?
in 1970 I believe it was.
I see.
Do you feel that your education at A&M prepared you for your current work?
Do you feel you were well prepared?
Some respects yes, some no.
Mine is not, I mean a contracting business is not, there are engineering opportunities there.
But there's also more business requirements than just the engineering.
Actually, we don't really do out and out engineering projects.
Ours is strictly a construction type operation.
And where more business would have helped me
more.
There are a few schools that have started whether they're still maintaining I'm not sure.
I believe Tulsa University was one.
A degree in that would lead to a degree in electrical contracting.
I see.
These are though through the National Electrical Contractors Association working with a university to
to get them set up, because there is some basic engineering needed, but also there's lots of business that it would help if you knew more of it earlier.
This sort of thing, and this is what I think this other course is trying to accomplish.
Are there any comments you feel you'd like to make?
If you look back over the whole era, do you feel there were any lost opportunities?
Oh, we were mentioning the hitchhiking and it came to mind that the hitchhiking was also kind of set up like the hazing.
That there was a specific corner in any given town
that you didn't ever start in front of that corner.
You could start there.
You could start anywhere on down the line.
But you didn't ever start ahead of that corner.
This was being called upstream.
You could go on down.
I can recall one time going to a football game in Dallas.
The corner was there in Bryan.
And when I got in the line, I was 103.
About an hour and a half later, I was out, but there was a code to the hitchhiking.
Only one stood out at the road.
The others were back away from the road.
If a car stopped, that one would ask, where are you going, how many will you take?
And if he was only going a short distance, and if you're in a long line, you're hoping for that long ride, and if you're up to the front, you might say, well,
you'll take two to Hearn and it starts down the line the first two down the line that wanted to go but but this uh really they had developed it to a real code of ethics.
Was there one then say you were going to Dallas was there a corner then in Dallas on the way back that you didn't start?
Yes yes there was nearly any town of any size there was now you may not always know it but pretty much it was
the center of town or some such thing as this.
Houston, it was on out on the north side of Houston.
It wasn't downtown there in the bigger towns.
It was out towards where the highways are.
There's not much question of which way you're going.
But you always had to start from that point.
Ethically, yes.
Ethically.
Were there any other rules to this hitchhiking game?
No, primarily just this idea that you represented A&M, you were courteous, you didn't go to sleep, you talked to them if they wanted to talk or sat there, but you observed these rules.
Was it easy or difficult to get a ride hitchhiking?
It was easy, pretty much.

I can recall one night spending all night over in Alice when my freshman year I still lived there in the valley but I found out later that a day or two before there'd been a hijacking or something of it by supposedly a hitchhiker and this word always hurt the hitchhiker but in the daytime where they could see the A&M uniform and what have you
They were always wellies.

I can recall my freshman year, the company commander and the battalion commander leaving, hitchhiking to Los Angeles to a football game, coming back through, changing their clothes and hitchhiking to New York to the one the next weekend.
This is getting along.
Hmm.
Anything else you recall?
They might want to be preserved.
You might want to have preserved.
No, not really.
Thank you very much.
